</p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#000000><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title><A HREF="http://www.ezboard.com/promotions/csc.html" TARGET="_blank" ><IMG SRC="http://www.ezboard.com/image/cscicon.gif" WIDTH="20" HEIGHT="20" BORDER="0" align="absmiddle"></A> <A HREF=http://pub23.ezboard.com/ulanoril.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Lanoril</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Forum Apprentice</span><br> <font color=#ffffff>(5/18/01 7:17:47 am)</font><br>     <br>Community Supporter<br> </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: This board always crack me up...</span><hr size=1> &quot;Fastasia, you're right that not every wizard gets to do aoe. But is that Verant's fault?&quot;<br>
<br>
Well, yeah.<br>
<br>
How so? There are two main reasons:<br>
<br>
(NOTE: The following assumes low/moderate twinkage; high twinking is an artifact of older servers, and does not account for more than 80% of the players' true experiences advancing from low levels from the beginning.)<br>
<br>
1) For 52 levels, there is no such thing as &quot;potent&quot; wizard AoE.  The damage PER MOB per mana (the only important measure of efficiency, because if you can't kill ONE mob with the AE, you certainly can't kill groups of them) is low (EDIT: Replaced &quot;high&quot; with &quot;low&quot;) enough that it would require more wizards than a group could  have and still have other necessary components (enchanter/bard and cleric/druid, depending on level).  In fact, the only reason 53+ AoE is viable is because any two (very skilled) or three (moderately skilled) wizards will be fine for nearly any AoE encounter.  Thus, for 52 levels AoE is certainly not a viable tactic, so people stick to other ones that are more powerful.  Why change suddenly after having had a lot of practice for 52 levels? (There is a legitimate counter to this question, which I shall address presently.)<br>
<br>
<br>
2) The world organisation/size. Norrath is, to put it bluntly, too small.  It's got lots of eye-candy and little  substance.  Any given level-range has a finite number of places in which to &quot;hunt.&quot;  The number of these places is <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i>  inversely</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> proportional the level-range.  That is, higher level ranges have fewer places to &quot;hunt&quot; than lower level ranges.  Ideally (from VI's perspective), there will correspondingly be fewer people in a given level range than the one before it.<br>
<br>
This is not the case, however.  VI has neglected a simple trait common to nearly every human being--&quot;comfortable&quot; environments.  Most people don't move regularly from house to house, or from job to job, simply because they develop an affinity for their current station.  The same is true in Norrath, as players inevitably project this sentiment to their characters.  Thus guilds and cliques form on any given server.<br>
<br>
Given this, and since every player will demand to &quot;hunt&quot; <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i>  somewhere</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> (inevitably they must if they are to advance their character), there must be some distribution of the huntable critters amongst the population.<br>
<br>
Now, 53+ AoE groups require quite specific classes.  A  cleric (very skilled druids or shamans might make do, but just barely; I've only ever tried once, and despite doing his best--and it was a damn good display--the shaman just couldn't handle the healing), a bard or enchanter (equally well, in my experience), and a &quot;puller&quot; (another bard or a tank of some sort).  The rest must consist of at least two wizards; preferably three.  Perhaps any combination of two wizards and a druid or 51+ magician (scintillation is nearly equivalent to Jyll's) would work on a good day.<br>
<br>
That is to say, <!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b>  an AoE group requires precisely the same &quot;core&quot; as any other group does.</b><!--EZCODE BOLD END-->  But the difficulty is <!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b>  much harder</b><!--EZCODE BOLD END--> than a Strategy(tm) (e.g., cleric, enchanter, caster, three tanks) group.<br>
<br>
And here's the kicker: because the number of &quot;huntable MOBs&quot; must be shared (or stolen--and that's a whole other bag of apples), there is very rarely, if ever, a place where the abundance of MOBs and scarcity of players make AoE as efficient as The Strategy(tm) (i.e., the mez-kill tactic).  <br>
<br>
Consider the numbers.  The 53+ AoE group has the potential to destroy from 10 to 20 or so MOBs per pull, and to do this two or three times before taking a &quot;med break.&quot; In my experience, it takes roughly 3 to 4 minutes to dispatch a group of MOBs with AoE.  So under ideal conditions, given that it takes approximately 15 minutes to &quot;med to full from zero&quot; with C2 at level 53+, an AoE group can destroy 60 MOBs in 24 minutes (ideal conditions, mind), or two MOBs per minute. Which is roughly three times the number a Strategy(tm) group could take given constant pulls. (This is the counter to the question posed in (1), above--why do it?  Because it's THREE TIMES the XP.)<br>
<br>
But in order to do this, there must be 60 MOBs available within the 24 minute span.  Now, my best estimate indicates that 60 MOBs at the 53+ level is a HUGE number.  It would encompass all of D1 and D2, and spill out into UZO and Necro in Old Sebilis, for example.<br>
<br>
How many times are all four of those places &quot;free?&quot; (Answer: never, on any server where Old Sebilis is hunted.)<br>
<br>
The natural counter is, &quot;So hunt somewhere else.&quot; Only, the <!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b>  same thing</b><!--EZCODE BOLD END--> is true of every other hunting ground that does not require a multi-group (2 or more) raid and has regular, short (i.e. less than 30 minutes or so) spawn times.  Why?  Because the number of places to hunt is small compared with the number of hunters. So 60 MOBS is a peak, ideal number.  Invariably, there will be fewer to hunt. Much fewer.<br>
<br>
And that, my friend, is not any player's fault. <p><font size=2>
