</font></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#33333><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub23.ezboard.com/ukelvyntelarian.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Kelvyn Telarian</A>&nbsp; <IMG HEIGHT=10 WIDTH=10 SRC=http://www.ezboard.com/ezgfx/globalBlack.gif BORDER=0></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Forum Wizard</span><br> <font color=#ffffff>(5/20/01 8:00:17 pm)</font><br>    </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: This board always crack me up...</span><hr size=1> I agree strongly with the original post here, and Beryl's overall thesis.  I view the context of the thesis a little differently though.  Grim is correct that AoE is not quite practical at all levels.  Certainly it becomes a whole new ballgame at 53 with Jylls. <br>
<br>
However, once chanters have at least 2 AE stuns, then 2 chanters, 2 wizzys, a cleric and a puller can group--that puller can be another AE nuke class or a melee, depending on how bold and how buffed the person is.<br>
<br>
As far as how common AoE grouping is, or how possible to make it common, this is really up to the Wizard community and casters in general.  We allowed ourselves to have the conditions for having a group be set by the melee community.  They HAD to have clerics and then chanters to function. Melees were initially the most popular class made by new players, and still are.  As a result, they set the tone for what was done most often.  Subsequently, people tended to make more melee classes than casters because they found they could get groups more easily, and did not have the downtime hassles or book to stare at (the book is one of the most horrible things VI ever came up with--they are kinda backing off it that now, but it should be reduced to level 20 where it is removed). <br>
<br>
Thus, we have things as they are today, the single-target model being the ideal means of play.  Now, I agree than in many, many situations, Single-target is the best, and perhaps only way to fight somethings. However, I believe many AoE opportunities are largely underutilized.  Furthermore, I think this is true across many levels of encounter, and that the popularity of the format can only be improved by assertive players forming these groups as often as possible. That takes effort, optimism and a view to the &quot;possible&quot; not the ever-focus on the &quot;impossible.&quot;<br>
<br>
If AoE could be popularized at more levels than 53+, people would make more casters, particularly enchanters and wizards, and the overall attitudes would change--also, more of these classes would be available for pickup situations. I don't know if I see that happening because the player base is rather set in its ways now, and many people tend to be pessimistic and rather un-adventurous. However, in either case, the model continues to server me well, and is really, as Beryl pointed out, so addicitve and successful, that once tried, people are hooked and will seek you out to get more. It is hard to ignore the kind of exp AoE generates, and the excitement as well.<br>
<br>
It is a shame this was moved to RANTS.  This thread could have been a huge help and inspiration to newer players. Perhaps a thread could be started on the general boards that is stated in such a way as to seek input and help showing how AoE groups can be formed, what members/spells are needed at what levels, and what zones/mobs are good for it.<br>
<br>
<br>
Kel,55,Ixtlan<br>
